  "doc_id": "18699",
  "text": "This high amount of ubiquitous molecular formulas in the FT-ICR-MS dataset enabled us to closely follow changes in temporal abundance of the majority of solid-phase extractable DOM. By referring to each molecular formula's abundance as the ratio of its maximum seasonal abundance [CITATION_1] , we gained valuable insights into seasonal trends of DOM dynamics. Another goal was to establish a set of molecular markers that are closely tied to the biogeochemistry of the Columbia River. The combination of optical and biogeochemical data with the FT-ICR mass spectra allowed the 30 identification of molecular formulas that contributed to the terrestrial input during the spring freshet. CDOM-correlated molecular formulas were predominantly CHO containing formulas, and were characterized by low H/C ratios, with aboveaverage numbers of double bonds. The high abundance of such molecular formulas during the spring freshet could therefore Biogeosciences Discuss., doi:10.5194/bg-2016 Discuss., doi:10.5194/bg- -263, 2016 Manuscript under review for journal Biogeosciences Published: 30 June 2016 c Author(s) 2016. CC-BY 3.0 License. explain shifts in SUVA 254 , BIX, and HIX. These findings agree with previous studies that linked chemical and optical properties of DOM [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and indicate the validity of these links across different aquatic environments.",
